events.name: Investment Club GBM #2
events.description: üì¢ About GBM 2 Our second General Body Meeting will focus on one of the most important steps in our club's journey, building and understanding our Initial Portfolio . During this meeting, we'll walk through how the portfolio is structured, the reasoning behind the investments chosen, and the balance of risks and opportunities it presents. If you weren't able to make it to our first meeting, that's completely okay, you'll still be able to jump right in and follow along. We'll make sure everyone has the context they need to get involved. This is a great chance to get a deeper look at the fundamentals of portfolio management, whether you're brand-new to investing or already have experience. We'll also open the floor for questions and discussion, so you'll have the opportunity to share your thoughts and learn from your peers. By the end of this session, you'll come away with a stronger understanding of how investment strategies are formed and how you can play an active role in shaping the future direction of our club!

events.name: Guest Speaker: Courtney Carlsson | Kin Therapy
events.description: Are you seeking out mental health therapy options? Curious what it's like to run a healthcare practice, from the business operations side? Join us for a conversation with Courtney Carlsson, MBA, to learn about Kin Therapy, a new virtual intensive outpatient program dedicated to supporting the mental health and emotional wellbeing of adolescents and young adults. Come with your questions and see how Kin Therapy is redefining mental health care for today's youth.    Our guest speaker is Courtney Carlsson. Courtney has a B.A. in Political Economy and Philosophy from Georgetown University and an MBA from London Business School. Additionally, she holds a certificate in Healthcare economics from Harvard Business School, certificate in Psychotherapy & Counselling from Regent's University London, and a Group Coaching Certificate from the Animas Centre for Coaching. As an entrepreneur in business as well as mental health advocate, she collaborated with psychologists, neuroscientists, and therapists to create Paradym, a self-help app that creates personalized exercises and feedback for users. Courtney now is co-founding her practice Kin Therapy.   üë§ Who:  HOPE members; non-members can join with a $5 donation to the club   üìÖ When: Wednesday, October 1st at 4:00 PM    üìçWhere: UCF Teaching Academy, Room 304   To join online: https://ucf.zoom.us/j/96314767822?pwd=NVVmgvCbdNzQZugHEupj0aCpfZae8q.1   Want to pre-submit a question? events.description: Spiritual Direction is the ancient practice of sitting with others while deeply listening and paying attention to the wisdom within.   Led by certified Spiritual Director Barb Shortal, this time will focus on truly listening to your words, feelings, thoughts, and even the silence‚Äîto help you uncover what is already within you. A spiritual director's role is to hold a compassionate, sacred space where you feel safe to explore, ask questions, wonder, and discern. Our time together is precious and always confidential.   All are welcome, regardless of faith or non-faith background.   Vision Board Workshop 8/28/25 Join us as we create vision boards as a way to visually express your hopes, values, and goals. This creative exercise will help you reflect on where you sense God (or the sacred) is leading you, setting the tone for deeper spiritual direction conversations throughout the semester.

events.name: SBC @ UCF 2nd General Body Meeting¬†‚Äì¬† LinkedIn + Resume Workshop: Thursday, October 2nd, 6:30 PM
events.description: Sport Business Club @ UCF will host its Second General Body Meeting (GBM) on Thursday, October 2, 2025, from 6:30‚Äì8:00 PM in Business Administration 1 (BA1), Room 218!  This event will focus on LinkedIn and Resume development ‚Äî two essential tools for students looking to stand out in today's competitive job market. The meeting will feature two guest speakers with valuable expertise: Amber Bonacci , Professional Development Coach in the College of Business, will explain what makes a resume stand out, what to cut, and how to tailor it for specific opportunities. She will also lead a resume "speed dating" session , where students can receive one-on-one feedback. Esteban Baez-Sola , an SBC @ UCF alumnus and well-regarded professional known for his ability to market himself effectively through LinkedIn, will demonstrate how to sharpen a LinkedIn profile, craft a personal brand, and leverage the platform for real opportunities. Beyond the presentations, the workshop is designed to be interactive. Students will have the chance to actively work on their resumes and LinkedIn profiles, ask direct questions, and receive actionable advice from both a professional coach and an alum with real-world experience. Attendees are strongly encouraged to bring their resumes and laptops to make the most of the session. Also, snacks and beverages will be provided throughout the evening! Event Details Date: Thursday, October 2, 2025 Time: 6:30 ‚Äì 8:00 PM Location: Business Administration 1 (BA1), Room 218 This GBM is an opportunity for members to invest in their future, connect with peers, and gain direct insight from professionals who know what it takes to succeed from a self-branding perspective!

events.name: Spiritual Direction with Wesley at UCF
events.description: Spiritual Direction is the ancient practice of sitting with others while deeply listening and paying attention to the wisdom within.   Led by certified Spiritual Director Barb Shortal, this time will focus on truly listening to your words, feelings, thoughts, and even the silence‚Äîto help you uncover what is already within you. A spiritual director's role is to hold a compassionate, sacred space where you feel safe to explore, ask questions, wonder, and discern. Our time together is precious and always confidential.   All are welcome, regardless of faith or non-faith background.   Vision Board Workshop 8/28/25 Join us as we create vision boards as a way to visually express your hopes, values, and goals. This creative exercise will help you reflect on where you sense God (or the sacred) is leading you, setting the tone for deeper spiritual direction conversations throughout the semester.

events.name: Spiritual Direction with Wesley at UCF
events.description: Spiritual Direction is the ancient practice of sitting with others while deeply listening and paying attention to the wisdom within.   Led by certified Spiritual Director Barb Shortal, this time will focus on truly listening to your words, feelings, thoughts, and even the silence‚Äîto help you uncover what is already within you. A spiritual director's role is to hold a compassionate, sacred space where you feel safe to explore, ask questions, wonder, and discern. Our time together is precious and always confidential.   All are welcome, regardless of faith or non-faith background.   Vision Board Workshop 8/28/25 Join us as we create vision boards as a way to visually express your hopes, values, and goals. This creative exercise will help you reflect on where you sense God (or the sacred) is leading you, setting the tone for deeper spiritual direction conversations throughout the semester.

events.description: ASA at UCF proudly presents our first-ever Global Cultural Film Festival! A sister event to the Orlando International Film Festival, led by Dr. Florence Alexander. GCFF focuses on uplifting underrepresented voices in the industry, including those from Asian, Black, Hispanic/Latino, Indigenous, Middle Eastern, and other diverse communities. We stop no one from submitting a film, regardless of its background. This in-person festival, held at UCF, provides a platform for emerging and established filmmakers to connect. organizations.name: Sigma Gamma Rho Sorority, Incorporated
organizations.description: Welcome to the home of the "Flipmode" Lambda Mu chapter of Sigma Gamma Rho Sorority, Inc. We are so delighted that you have stopped by to browse and to learn more about what Lambda Mu does here at The University Of Central Florida . As part of the illustrious sisterhood of Sigma Gamma Rho, we hold dear to our hearts high scholastic achievement, genuine community outreach, and the elegance that distinguishes successful young women from girls.     In the Spring of 1990, there was a need to finally complete the list of historically black sororities at the University of Central Florida. Therefore, with the help of the Delta Mu Sigma Alumnae Chapter , Lambda Mu's Herstory was created. The void was filled by nine vibrant young women. These women represent four different countries: Antigua, Italy, the Philippines, and the United States. Their main focus of studies concentrated in the following disciplines: the study of life, educational development, business, and the intricacy of engineering. They are the Sorors of "NINE LIVES"

We strive to promote sincere friendship, academic excellence, high standards of personal integrity, dedication to others through service, credible career and personal development, and unwavering community involvement. Our values guide us to grow. They allow generations of women to work towards balance in our lives, on our campuses, and within our communities.   Being part of Chi Omega is more than drawers full of lettered t-shirts, more than themed functions, and more than a few extra likes on Instagram. Chi Omega is a sisterhood. It is a house to call home and friends to call family. A place to turn tears into laughter. And a place to become the best version of yourself. I hope you get the chance to walk through our big red doors and meet the incredible women that make Psi Mu a home and ensure that Chi Omega is the sisterhood it was founded to be 127 years ago.

organizations.name: Caribbean Students' Association
organizations.description: Caribbean St udents' Association at The University of Central Florida History The Caribbean Students' Association at the University of Central Florida (CSA at UCF) has a short and colorful history. In April 1985, the idea for a Caribbean Club was concieved and acted upon by a few dedicated students, who spent many days trying to solicit enough signatures to officially activate the organization. The Caribbean Club, as it was called, served as a "home away from home" for the many Caribbean students at UCF. The club was formed with the purpose of fostering a cultural bridge between the Caribbean and the United States. In the Spring of 1990, the club was reactivated. It was tough in the beginning, but the hardwork and persistence finally paid off in the Spring of 1992 when the Caribbean Students' Association was officially formed and the membership blossomed from 15 to 100 members. The hard work and persistence finally paid off.  The Club meetings provide a relaxed atmosphere for students to meet and network. Students of all cultures were encouraged to share their Caribbean heritage while keeping the traditions of their Caribbean ancesto rs. Today, our membership has increased to over 300 students. Dedicated members are the key to the success of CSA. In 1992 our Association at UCF became one of the five educational institutions that started the Florida Caribbean Students' Association and is one of the initial five organizations at UCF to become apart of the university's MultiCultural Student Center. Today, CSA is one of the most active Student Organizations on the University of Central Florida campus.   C S A gives a special thanks to: Las Adams, Elton Bracey, Victor Flores, Barry Brennen, Kisha Dunn, Tricia Phillip, Deanna Hoyen, Alfredo Barrett Jr., Patrice Phillip, Denise Green, Drumeco Lauritson, Gordan McKenzie, Jason Isree, Jey Singam, Yonette Forde, Sharon Cruz, Lisa Pitram, Andrea Brown.   Most of All: Raymond Permaul Lynette Permaul Jameer Abass Edmund Dabiedah and Anne Marie de Govia

organizations.description: Omicron Delta Kappa, the National Leadership Honor Society, was founded December 3, 1914 at Washington and Lee University in Lexington, Virginia by 15 student and faculty leaders. The founders formulated the idea that leadership of exceptional quality and versatility in college should be recognized, that representatives in all phases of college life should cooperate in worthwhile endeavors, and that outstanding students, faculty, and administrators should meet on a basis of mutual interest, understanding, and helpfulness.  OΔK¬Æ was the first college honor society of a national scope to give recognition and honor for meritorious leadership and service in extracurricular activities and to encourage development of general campus citizenship. Since its founding, Omicron Delta Kappa has initiated over 300,000 members. The Society recognizes achievement in the following five areas: Scholarship Athletics Campus or Community Service, Social or Religious Activities and Campus Government Journalism, Speech and the Mass Media Creative and Performing Arts   If you are interested in joining, please visit our website to complete the online application at: https://membership.odk.org/audience/prospective_members/membership_application_form

organizations.description: The mission of the Herpetological Society is to inspire passion and respect for our Florida reptiles and amphibians. Because herpetofauna is societally misunderstood, we aim to educate against common misconceptions and mitigate irrational fears, while teaching how to safely interact with these animals.

organizations.name: American Marketing Association at UCF
organizations.description: Welcome to The American Marketing Association at the University of Central Florida page!   Our members will not just be standing in the back and blending in the crowd.  The organization encourages everyone - of all and any majors -  to engage and interact with others, learn from business professionals through our interactive events, professional workshops, and network with others to share knowledge and further advance their career endeavors.   How do I join? To become a member, please follow the steps on our site amaucf.org ! Then, fill out the membership form in our LinkTree ! Join our Mailing List! Be the first to know when we are on campus by  joining here!

organizations.name: Tau Beta Pi - The Engineering Honor Society
organizations.description: About Tau Beta Pi Tau Beta Pi is the only engineering honor society representing the entire engineering profession. It is the nation's second-oldest honor society, founded at Lehigh University in 1885 to mark in a fitting manner those who have conferred honor upon their Alma Mater by distinguished scholarship and exemplary character as students in engineering, or by their attainments as alumni in the field of engineering, and to foster a spirit of liberal culture in engineering colleges. There are now collegiate chapters at 246 US colleges and universities, 40 active alumni chapters in 16 districts across the country, and a total initiated membership of approximately 580,000.   Future TBP Members Interested in joining or qualifications for membership? Membership in Tau Beta Pi is by invitation from our collegiate chapters to students in the top 1/8 of the junior class or top 1/5 of the senior class. Graduate students and eminent engineers may also be initiated.  Find out more here »

organizations.name: Women's Lacrosse Club @ UCF
organizations.description: The Womens Lacrosse Team at UCF is a competitive team that competes in both local and nation-wide tournaments. We travel to other Florida schools and out of state schools to compete. We have mandatory practices three times a week :)

organizations.name: Sailing Club @ UCF
organizations.description: Please reach out to us at sailingucf@gmail.com for any questions.   Our site has moved to IMLeagues UCF, you can find us through the RWC Website under "Sport Clubs." If you are looking to contact the club please use any of our other methods of contact (email, groupme, instagram, etc.) We look forward to hearing from you!   Mission The mission of Sailing Club at UCF is to provide students an opportunity to learn and compete in the sport of sailing.   Goals Our goals are to provide all sailors an opportunity to improve in their craft and represent the University of Central Florida on the regional and national stage.

organizations.name: Girls Who Code at UCF
organizations.description: Girls Who Code at UCF is dedicated to closing the gender gap in technology and computer science. Our goal is to inspire more girls to learn coding and pursue a career in the computer science field. We value diversity, equity, and inclusion. We acknowledge that historical and institutional barriers‚Äîparticularly racial bias and discrimination‚Äîplay a role in the widening gender gap in computer science and who has access to opportunities in these fields. Girls Who Code focuses our work not only on gender diversity but also on young women who are historically underrepresented in computer science fields. We want to provide our members with a safe space to learn, create and become part of a supportive community that will help them achieve their personal and professional goals. Join our discord:  https://discord.gg/9k8qtP7teX

organizations.name: UCF Arboretum
organizations.description: To volunteer with us, please click Join !    Individual Volunteering   Students, faculty, and staff can sign up to volunteer in our Greenhouse, Pollinator Gardens, Public Garden landscapes, and Community Farm and Gardens. Each shift has a cap of 6-10 people, depending on project needs.  To RSVP, please scroll down to the Events section. Choose the volunteer shift you'd like to RSVP to. Once on the details page for the event, click RSVP. If it shows "No Spots Available", our shift is full, but feel free to join the waitlist. We post shifts at the end of each month! Any forms that need to be signed must be accompanied by hours submitted through this section.   For Adopt-A-Program volunteer inquiries, please contact adopt.a.program@ucf.edu. Group Volunteering is suspended until further notice.    Please contact us through our email ( arboretum@ucf.edu ) or our Instagram @ucfarboretum   Arboretum Documentary:   https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6X7WyiVMpwE

organizations.name: Bachelors of Social Work Student Association
organizations.description: The Bachelors of Social Work Student Association (BSWSA) is an organization that links undergraduate social work students to their community and peers to better enrich their educational experience at the University of Central Florida. BSWSA members benefit from service learning projects, workshops, guest speakers and a community of friendly, like-minded individuals that will one day make up the profession of social work.  The BSWSA encourages any student interested in social service, community resources, and social justice to join us. Follow us on Instagram at @bswsa.ucf

organizations.name: Chi Upsilon Sigma National Latin Sorority, Inc.
organizations.description: Alpha Xi was founded at the University of Central Florida on January 9, 2006.  After a few years of hard work and dedication, we were welcomed to the Diversified Greek Council in 2009.  Alpha Xi has grown to over 60 women as of today.  The chapter concentrates on presenting relevant and controversial programming centered on social, political, educational, and cultural awareness'.  Alpha Xi also focuses on community service through our chapter philanthropy, Harbor House of Central Florida and our national philanthropy, I Have a Dream Foundation, amongst many others. Our goals also include maintaining high GPAs and actively contributing to the scholastic achievement of the Greek Community.

organizations.name: Sparks Magazine at the University of Central Florida
organizations.description: The purpose of Sparks magazine is to foster understanding and appreciation of the Asian Pacific Islander American experience. The vision of Sparks magazine is to become a resource for the Asian and Pacific Islander American community that steers the movement for social change.

organizations.name: SoberKnights
organizations.description: Mission The mission of SoberKnights is to foster friendships that support a sober lifestyle and encourage students to have fun while in college without feeling peer pressure to use drugs and alcohol, all while breaking down the stigma that surrounds addiction and substance abuse. Goals SoberKnights seeks to support UCF's goal of becoming a more diverse and inclusive community by educating and supporting both students and staff. Our main goal as an organization is to create a nurturing environment for UCF students in recovery. Another equally important goal is to break through the stigma surrounding addiction. Many members can attest to the stereotypes that are subconsciously projected upon anyone in recovery: "moral failing", "junkie", "untrustworthy", "degenerate" ‚Äî a few phrases that are sometimes associated with addiction. None of these are true of those suffering from addiction! Students in recovery from addiction are just as capable as any other student group, and SoberKnights wants to make sure UCF's community knows this.

organizations.description: - Mission: To help guide the men at UCF into the leaders that God called them to be - Goals: Community: Embracing one other by sharing each other's experiences and uplift one another's circumstances Welcoming Environment: Celebrating and acknowledging different backgrounds and talents from all walks of life to bring a comforting environment to express themselves and help impact the community around us Personal Growth: Bettering each other's decision-making skills with their walk with God, their career, relationships, finances, etc.

organizations.description: The purpose of our organization is to prepare our members to become well-informed, exceptional candidates when applying to dental school. Not only is this a great place to learn more about the field of dentistry, but to also build a supportive community at UCF! We invite you to learn more about us and all of the great resources we have to offer!     If you would like to join our organization, please pay your membership dues on our website PDSAUCF.com . organizations.name: Emergency Management Student Association
organizations.description: The Emergency Management Student Association seeks to bridge the gap between Emergency Management from a classroom perspective and Emergency Management in the real world. organizations.name: National Society of Black Engineers
organizations.description: The National Society of Black Engineers (NSBE) is the largest student-run organization in the nation , committed to advancing the academic, professional, and personal success of its members. At our chapter, we host events throughout the academic year that promote academic excellence, technical growth, leadership, and community service.   Check out our  website   for more information . Also, follow us on  Instagram   and join our  Discord   to stay up to date on our events!   Our efforts extend beyond college campuses through our Pre-College Initiative (PCI) program, where we inspire and support youth in pursuing higher education and careers in STEM . From mentorship to hands-on workshops, we aim to build a strong pipeline of future engineers.   In addition to our core programming, we offer general socials and chapter bonding experiences that help cultivate a welcoming, supportive community. As a chapter, we are dedicated to empowering our members to grow academically, professionally, and personally.

organizations.name: Neuroscience Alliance at UCF
organizations.description: The mission of Neuroscience Alliance at UCF is to promote awareness, research, and opportunities in neuroscience at UCF. By encouraging professional relations between students and faculty, students will be provided with opportunities and exposure in current research, potential career paths, and provided with advice and information for a future career in neuroscience. These goals shall be achieved through providing meetings and speeches related to neuroscience, potential outreach in the form of shadowing neuroscience related professionals, volunteering at schools, hospitals, or other such facilities, and creating committees involving projects and ideas relevant to neuroscience within any area such as medicine, philosophy, psychology, biotechnology, psychiatry, computer science, chemistry, cognitive science, linguistics, mathematics, engineering, and physics.

organizations.name: Women's Water Polo Club @ UCF
organizations.description: Women's Water Polo at UCF is a competitive club team that travels within the Southeast region (Florida and Georgia) during the regular season and across the US for Nationals. We have been ranked among the top 10 teams in the Nation three times, once in the top 2. Rankings at Nationals: 2013- 2nd | 2015- 9th | 2017- 5th | 2022- 12th SE Division Champs: 2009-10 | 2013 | 2015 | 2017  SE Runner-up: 2011-12 | 2014 | 2016 | 2018 | 2022 There are no tryouts or experience required to be a part of our team, however, a background in swimming is recommended. The (2025) Fall semester practices are TBD.

organizations.name: Knight Runners
organizations.description: We are the official running club at UCF! Knight Runners is a club that accomodates both recreational AND competitive skill-levels and provides a community for runners at UCF. We practice each week Monday-Thursday at the RWC at 6:00PM, and we also meet up on weekends for local races, long runs, or travel events. You are encouraged to come as much or as little as you want!  We are also a member of the National Intercollegiate Running Club Association. We participate in Fall and Spring out of state post-season competitions.  Follow our Instagram (@knightrunnersatucf), or send us an email (knightrunnersucf@gmail.com) for more up to date information.   We hope to see you out there! (we are active in SUMMER)

organizations.name: Young Democratic Socialists of America at UCF
organizations.description: By mobilizing, organizing, and educating the students at UCF, YDSA at UCF aims to engage students in the process of activism and educate students about the principles and merits of democratic socialism. YDSA at UCF  aims to conduct numerous events to accomplish this goal. Throughout the academic year, we will host mutual aid events, support charity efforts on campus, and host various other volunteering events like these to engage our members in the activism process.

organizations.name: Chinese American Student Association
organizations.description: The Chinese American Student Association aims to provide a community for Chinese-American students at the University of Central Florida, as well as introduce authentic Chinese culture to anyone interested in learning. We are excited to serve our members by providing a wide variety of culturally-immersive events, including monthly GBMs and other social activities! The Chinese American Student Association celebrates all backgrounds and embraces all cultures.

organizations.name: Arnold Air Society
organizations.description: Arnold Air Society is a professional, honorary service organization advocating the support of aerospace power. We are dedicated to creating proactive, knowledgeable, and effective civic leaders through community service and education about national defense. It is made up largely of civilians and Air Force ROTC cadets interested in personal development, leadership, service, and support of our military personnel

organizations.name: Association of Doctoral Students in Exceptional Education
organizations.description: The Association of Doctoral Students in Exceptional Education is a professional organization that focuses on supporting doctoral students through research and their dissertations.

organizations.name: American Medical Women's Association
organizations.description: The American Medical Women's Association aims to foster an enriching environment for women in science and the medical profession. We hope to create a supportive and collaborative community for all women pursuing careers in the health professions through events such as clinical skills workshops, resume building events, and hearing from inspiring female professionals.   Follow our Instagram for all updated information @amwaucf

organizations.name: Antioch Orlando College Ministry
organizations.description: We are an on-campus college ministry which is a part of our local church, Antioch Community Church Orlando.   Our desire is to see college students transformed through knowing Jesus, being plugged into the local church, and impacting our city and the nations with the Gospel.   We meet weekly in what we call "Lifegroups" to connect, share how God is moving in our lives, encourage and pray for one another, spend time in worship, and have biblical discussions. Our Lifegroups meet different evenings of the week both on and off campus so there should be a good fit for anyone's schedule!   We also meet weekly with the rest of our church on Sunday mornings at 10:30am.   For more information on where we meet, what we believe and upcoming mission trips please check out our website: AntiochOrlando.com

organizations.name: Financial Knights Association
organizations.description: The Financial Knights Association is dedicated to preparing UCF students for elite finance careers, including but not limited to investment banking, equity research, sales and trading, and private equity. We aim to connect students with industry leaders, providing the technical skills, mentorship, and exposure needed to excel in these competitive fields. Our goal is to equip students with the knowledge and experience necessary to thrive in high finance roles.

organizations.name: Sigma Lambda Gamma National Sorority Incorporated
organizations.description: During the fall of 1989, the foundation of Sigma Lambda Gamma National Sorority, Inc. was commenced by collegiate women who recognized the need to form an organization that provided empowerment to women of all cultural backgrounds. Their humble beginnings were built at the University of Iowa, Iowa City, Iowa where their vision was to create a network of academic and social support for all women/nonbinary. Under the guidance of Esther Materon Arum and Mary Peterson, the vision came to fruition on April 9th, 1990, as the University of Iowa Panhellenic Council officially recognized the organization as a sorority. Through the continued commitment and leadership of the founding mothers, the operation of Sigma Lambda Gamma has thrived on many college campuses and provides an avenue for educational excellence to women of many nationalities. Our members recognize the need for togetherness and support among members of varying cultures at the university level and they remain dedicated to the overall success of members in a global environment. Sigma Lambda Gamma is a sisterhood/siblinghood of members who have chosen this affiliation as a manner to achieve personal development and awareness to the responsibility of community involvement for the betterment of our local, regional, national and global communities through the efforts of a network of close to 3,000 sorority members. Furthermore, we continue to be a pioneer in the Greek fraternal world through development of innovative programming initiatives, such as the Young Women's Leadership Program and Emotional Intelligence. Today, Sigma Lambda Gamma is the largest and fastest-growing multicultural sorority with a multicultural membership in chapters and alumnae associations throughout the United States ‚Äì from Arizona to Wyoming; Florida to Minnesota; New York to Texas; and many more states between the coasts of California and Rhode Island. A criterion for membership into Sigma Lambda Gamma is open to members of exceptional morals & ethics with a demonstrated commitment to academic excellence, and who are pursuing or have completed courses leading to a degree in an accredited college of university. Sigma Lambda Gamma is welcome to women, trans women, and nonbinary. Culture is Pride, Pride is Success.

organizations.name: Mexican Student Association
organizations.description: Mission The mission of Mexican Student Association is to serve as liaison between the Mexican community and the UCF community to support and unite Mexican students at UCF. MexSA is committed to providing social, cultural, and educational awareness amongst the UCF community about the Mexican people. Goals The goal of MexSA is to unite students at UCF to help and support each other throughout their educational journey at UCF. MexSA, as UCF, stands for opportunity. This organization will make sure that its members excel at UCF by providing them proper leadership and personal growth experiences. MexSA will offer a safe, comfortable, and judgement-free environment for students to come together and smoothly adjust to the campus life. Discussions about personal experiences and cultural diversity will serve as the primary source for developing harmony and friendship among all its members and the rest of UCF student body. MexSA, as the acting Mexican institution at UCF, will look after the educational and social development and progress of the Mexican community within Orlando, especially in the University of Central Florida.

organizations.name: Phi Alpha National Social Work Honor Society
organizations.shortName: Phi Alpha National Social Work Honor Society
organizations.description: Phi Alpha Nation Social Work Honor Society members benefit from joining Phi Alpha in Inter-Professional Education (IPE), Induction Ceremony, Social Network Events, Workshop Opportunities, and Lifelong National Membership. Being a member is more than beautiful graduation cords. This organization is nationally recognized for service learning, emphasizing academic achievements and promoting humanitarian goals.

organizations.name: HOPE @ UCF
organizations.description: How to Join HOPE as a member:  Complete the 2025-2026 Membership Application Pay dues: Venmo, Credit, Debit, or PayPal. Click the links below!  $15 ‚Äî  2 Semester HOPE UCF Membership $10 ‚Äî  1 Semester HOPE UCF Membership   If you cannot use the above options, you can pay through cash at a general body meeting of HOPE.   Submit your request on Knight Connect to join as a member.  Stay up to date:  Follow on Instagram Join on the HOPE GroupMe  HOPE @ UCF was founded by two students who are passionate about peer support and preventing suicide. We believe that college can be an overwhelming time, and that we don't have to go through it alone ‚Äì through supporting one another, we become beacons of hope on our campus, in our friendships, in the workplace, and in the world.    HOPE's mission is to create a community where students of all backgrounds and fields of study feel supported, destigmatize conversations about mental health, build meaningful relationships, and engage in self-care and high-impact community service.    A key goal of HOPE is for all of our members to take suicide prevention training, such as Question, Persuade, Refer (QPR), at least once during their time as a Knight!    Our club offers:    Mentorship program: Students are matched into groups of 3, with at least one upper-class student mentor. Each semester centers around a new theme related to mental health (self-care, volunteer service, building community, etc.)  High impact volunteer opportunities: We prioritize opportunities where students gain hands-on experience with populations in need and serve their community in meaningful ways.   Suicide Prevention Training: Our club hosts QPR sessions each semester and promotes opportunities in the community.  Professional development events: We host guest speakers in the fields of psychology, mental health, and related fields for interactive workshops.  Socials: Fun events for students to network, make friends, and practice self-care.  Our goal is to unite students across professions who want to be mental health advocates in their communities.

organizations.name: Men's Ultimate Frisbee Club @ UCF
organizations.description: Men's Ultimate Frisbee at UCF is a traveling, competitive sport club. The sport of Ultimate is physically demanding but tremendously fun. It complements certain rules of American football and soccer with those that make Ultimate unique. The club boasts two highly successful teams: the Dogs of War (A-team) and Havoc (B-team). Regardless of skill, a spot is always guaranteed on the team. If you play, you'll notice a tremendously quick improvement and will have experiences you'll never forget.   PRACTICE TIMES: Tuesday: 8 to 11 Turf Field 6 Thursday: 5 to 8 North Grass

organizations.name: Sport Business Club @ UCF
organizations.description: Sport Business Club @ UCF is a premier undergraduate organization dedicated to preparing students for influential careers in the sports, entertainment, and media industries. Grounded in experiential learning and strategic industry engagement, SBC provides members with opportunities to develop critical business skills, explore emerging trends, and connect with leading professionals across the country. Through speaker panels, site visits, competitions, leadership development programs, and collaborative projects, the club bridges the gap between academic theory and real-world application. Members are encouraged to lead with purpose, think critically about the evolving sports landscape, and engage with ethical, inclusive practices that reflect the complexities of modern sport business. SBC is deeply committed to creating a space that reflects the diverse voices, backgrounds, and ambitions of UCF's student body. By promoting equity in access, representation, and leadership, the club ensures that all students‚Äîincluding first-generation and underrepresented populations‚Äîhave a pathway into high-impact roles in the industry. Backed by partnerships with the DeVos Sport Business Management Program and a growing national network, SBC is building one of the most dynamic, student-driven sport business ecosystems in the country. Whether you aspire to work in team operations, marketing, law, analytics, or media, the Sport Business Club @ UCF is where future leaders begin their journey. We appreciate all our members for their dedication and enthusiasm, which propel our community forward. Thank you for your commitment and contributions that enrich our collective experience and success.   How do I join? 1) Register on KnightConnect! 2) Join our Flare! (This is where all our important dates, opportunities, meeting times, etc, are all posted!) 3) Fill out the Membership Form & pay dues* (instructions on the linked Google Form!) NOTE: If, for any reason, you are unable to pay dues but would still like to be a member of SBC @ UCF, please email ab081126@ucf.edu, and we will make sure to work something out!

organizations.name: International City/County Management Association

Wine Club
organizations.description: The UCF Wine Club focuses on enhancing and furthering members' knowledge of the industry and the amazing world of wine. The primary purpose of the club is to introduce our members to different wines from around the world and explore wine in the business around Orlando. We taste and evaluate each wine while discussing geographic factors and production methods which shape the individual wines. Our tastings are lead by a variety of guest speakers from the industry who also discuss their professional journeys and provide insight towards turning a passion for wine into a career. We also offer unique opportunities and site visits for members to see different facets of the industry up close. Please be sure to RSVP for each meeting so we know how much wine to have prepared. Follow us on Instagram, TikTok, and LinkedIn (@ucfwineclub)!  ** Must be 21+ to attend **

organizations.name: Cuban American Student Association
organizations.description: We hope to participate in socials, service opportunities and involvement in cultural events, like Hispanic Heritage month and Cuban Independence Day. Our organization will benefit the student body by providing a safe space for students and being a bridge for others to learn about our culture. Follow us on Instagram  @casaatucf and join our GroupMe  for more updates.

organizations.name: Students Supporting Israel at the University of Central Florida
Alpha Kappa Psi - Nu Chi
organizations.shortName: Alpha Kappa Psi, Co-Ed Professional Business Fraternity
organizations.description: Alpha Kappa Psi is the oldest and largest professional co-ed business fraternity founded in 1904 at New York University. Open to all majors, we are dedicated to providing a diverse platform to enhance leadership skills, expand professional networks, and engage in meaningful personal and career development.  Through a variety of activities such as workshops and networking events, we extend beyond professional development with active participation in community service and philanthropic initiatives. Alpha Kappa Psi has a prestigious alumni network comprised of successful professionals and entrepreneurs across various industries. In essence, Alpha Kappa Psi is more than a Fraternity‚Äîit is a vibrant community shaping future business leaders!

organizations.name: Baptist Collegiate Ministries
organizations.description: BCM (Baptist Collegiate Ministries) is a Christian community at UCF with the Gospel as our center and scripture as our guide. Our mission is to bring in, build up, and send out students by showing them the joy of a life dedicated to knowing Jesus. While BCM does stand for Baptist Collegiate Ministries, we are not exclusively Baptist. We receive support from the Florida Baptist Convention and Baptist churches. Any one and everyone is welcome no matter their background!   To best keep up with BCM, be sure to check out our website ucfbcm.com or follow us on Instagram at @ucfbcm!

organizations.name: Bowling Club @ UCF
organizations.description: The Bowling Club @ UCF is a collegiate travel team that bowls competitively within all USBC teams. Every year we battle some of the biggest schools in bowling amongst the US Southeast and even venture across the nation for select events! We compete both Fall and Spring semesters with a nurturing but competitive team environment. Not a competitive bowler? No worries, our team is open to all and regardless of where you stand, we want to help you improve! Join us for practices Monday 7-9pm at Boardwalk Bowl located on Colonial Drive! Join our discord: https://discord.gg/gzyKMMnRrK

organizations.name: Upsilon Phi Delta Healthcare Administration Honor Society
organizations.description: Upsilon Phi Delta is a select and distinguished national academic honor society for students studying healthcare administration. Our organization's mission is to recognize, reward, and encourage academic excellence in the study of health administration.  Please see "Documents" section for membership eligibility information and the application.   ‚Äã‚ÄãUpsilon: meaning "Health"; Phi: meaning "Care"; Delta: meaning "to lead and administer"   Find the application with the requirements for admission in the documents below!

organizations.name: Alpha Iota Sigma International Interdisciplinary Studies Honor Society
Phi Alpha Theta Honor Society
organizations.shortName: Phi Alpha Theta History Honor Society
organizations.description: Phi Alpha Theta History Honor Society encompasses social and academic interests of undergraduate and graduate students at UCF.

organizations.name: Epilepsy Awareness Club
organizations.description: Founded in Fall 2022, the Epilepsy Awareness Club at the University of Central Florida is dedicated to spreading knowledge and awareness, while also providing support, to those affected by epilepsy - a disorder that is often overlooked and affects so many, especially right here on our college campus.   Through hosting our events and fundraisers on UCF campus, we are able to bring awareness to epilepsy, as well as raise donations to aid in informing and research.   The EAC is also committed to collaborating with other organizations outside of our home campus and act as representatives for the students at UCF.

organizations.name: Delta Delta Delta Fraternity
organizations.description: Tri delta is a Panhellenic Sorority with about 150 women. We have been on this campus for decades with a strong support system for one another and alumna base. Tri delta focuses on truth, self sacrifice, and friendship with a key focus on our philanthropy St. Jude Children's Research Hospital. Tri delta is extremely active on and on campus with many women active in other organizations. Tri Delta is more than just a sorority and will last so much longer than four years.

organizations.name: Grass Volleyball Club
organizations.description: Join our discord for information and updates! https://discord.gg/cjfkyfP4Nz

organizations.name: Muslim Student Association
organizations.description: The mission of MSA at UCF is to provide, in accordance with the teachings of Islam, religious services, social services, academic services, and community services along with spreading the logical and beautiful message of Islam and engaging in interfaith.  linktr.ee/Msa_ucf

organizations.name: Students for Salt
organizations.description: The Mission for Students for Salt is to build up and empower collegiate student leaders to impact the campus and community for Christ through outreach and service. We aim to connect current students with community members who share their faith and desire for service within a local faith-centered community. We are affiliated with Salt Company National. A national organization that started in 1987 to reach major universities in North America.    Our goal is to reach the campus through students and equip them to love, serve and lead on the campus now and later lead in the community themselves.     We have weekly gatherings, campus groups, mentorship, and service opportunities for UCF students to connect in and grow their faith.

organizations.name: Perfect Pair
organizations.description: The UCF chapter of Perfect Pair has some of the following goals: Enhancing the quality of life of older adults: The primary goal of Perfect Pair is to enrich the lives of the elderly by providing them with companionship and emotional support. The UCF chapter of Perfect Pair may seek to achieve this goal by organizing regular visits, community events, and other activities that allow older adults to interact with college students. Building meaningful relationships: Perfect Pair aims to foster genuine connections between older adults and college students. The UCF chapter may strive to create opportunities for long-term relationships to form, which can provide both parties with a sense of purpose and fulfillment. Providing volunteer opportunities: College students who participate in Perfect Pair gain valuable experience in volunteering and serving the community. The UCF chapter may seek to provide students with meaningful volunteer opportunities that allow them to make a difference in the lives of others. Raising awareness about older adult loneliness: Perfect Pair recognizes that loneliness is a widespread issue, and aims to raise awareness about it. The UCF chapter may strive to educate the local community about the importance of addressing this problem and encouraging more people to get involved in helping seniors. Perfect Pair is a non-profit organization, and the UCF chapter may need to fundraise to support their efforts. The chapter may organize events and activities to raise funds that can be used to support their programs and cover the costs of providing activities and resources for the seniors they serve.

organizations.name: Engineers Without Borders
organizations.description: Welcome to the official Knight Connect page for EWB at UCF! Our mission:  Engineers Without Borders USA (EWB-USA) is a nonprofit humanitarian organization established to support community-driven development programs worldwide through partnerships that design and implement sustainable engineering projects, while creating transformative experiences that enrich global perspectives and create responsible leaders. Our vision:  EWB-USA's vision is a world in which the communities we serve have the capacity to sustainably meet their basic human needs. Today, more than two billion people lack access to the most basic things -- clean drinking water, adequate sanitation, reliable passage to local markets and more. Join our GroupMe for more info:  https://groupme.com/join_group/102377822/y9CKRCvY

organizations.name: Knights Exemplar
organizations.description: Knights Exemplar supports UCF's Inclusive Education Services (IES) students as they complete their Professional Service Credential requirements. The mission of the IES program is to provide learning experiences, within an inclusive educational setting, for young adults with intellectual disabilities, university students, faculty, staff, and community leaders.  Members will serve as Involvement Ambassadors (IAs), a peer mentor of the highest quality. IAs are role models and persons of support to the IES student he or she works with. IAs support IES students in the areas of academics (i.e. tutoring, scheduling), campus activity (i.e. connecting with other RSOs, on-campus resources, attending football games), career exploration (i.e. career services workshops, resume creation, career and internship support) health and wellness (i.e. RWC workout partner, lunch meeting partner), all while gaining social skills through the building of positive and trusting relationships.

organizations.name: Nike Community
organizations.description: To provide a residence life program that encourages a positive living and learning environment, supportive of students development in the college community by providing quality opportunities and connections for academic and personal growth.   The Nike Area Council is dedicated to building a fun and inclusive atmosphere in the Nike Community at UCF!

organizations.name: Pre-Medical American Medical Student Association
organizations.description: Pre-Med AMSA helps our members with research positions, shadowing physicians, and volunteering in a hospital setting throughout Orlando while also offering over 45 leadership positions. We strive to bring all the elements of a well-rounded medical school applications to our members. Pre-Med AMSA also has physicians, medical student panels and always some aspect of medicine at our general body meetings to provide our members with valuable experiences.

organizations.name: Girl Up Orlando
organizations.description: Girl Up Orlando is an organization that strives to empower students by channeling their energy and compassion to raise awareness for the United Nations initiatives that help hard to reach adolescent girls. We want to bring together men and women from all different backgrounds to get involved and help out in whichever way they find suitable. We want t o make sure that girls in developing countries are healthy, safe, educated, accounted for, and positioned to be the next generation of leaders through fundraising and advocacy.

organizations.name: Psi-Chi International Honor Society of Psychology - Lake Mary
organizations.description: Psi Chi is an international honor society that awards academic recognition to students who achieve scholastic excellence  in the study of psychology. The UCF-Lake Mary chapter of Psi Chi hosts meetings and events in the pursuit of encouraging and stimulating the academic and professional growth of its members.

organizations.name: Biotech Alliance of Medicine
organizations.description: The mission of Biotech Alliance of Medicine is to inform aspiring scholars about the advancements being made in medicine with the use of technology. With the help of professionals within the field, we hope to open the eyes of society to the endless possibilities provided through biotechnology.

organizations.name: Pride Student Association
organizations.description: Looking for more LGBTQ+ friends? Pride Student Association is committed to celebrating and unifying the LGBTQ+ community on the UCF campus. Mission : The Pride Student Association is dedicated to fostering a vibrant and inclusive environment for the LGBTQ+ community at UCF. Our mission is to celebrate diversity, promote unity, and empower individuals by providing a platform for networking, education, advocacy, and social engagement. Purpose : Networking and Socializing: Through regular meetings and events organized by the Pride Student Association and local affiliates, we offer opportunities for LGBTQ+ students to connect, build friendships, and create a supportive network within the UCF community. Discussion and Intersectionality: We facilitate open and critical discussions about current events affecting the LGBTQ+ community, emphasizing intersectionality and the experiences of gender and sexual minorities that often go overlooked in broader conversations. Inclusion and Acceptance: Our organization strives to include and amplify the voices of gender and sexual minorities who are often marginalized within the larger LGBTQ+ community. We seek to create a safe space where all individuals feel heard, valued, and supported. Social and Political Outreach: We engage in social and political outreach activities to support representatives and candidates who share our goal of LGBTQ+ inclusion and acceptance. By advocating for policy changes and promoting LGBTQ+ rights, we aim to effect positive societal change. Education and Awareness: Through various events, we aim to educate and raise awareness among the UCF student body and local residents about the LGBTQ+ community. Our goal is to foster understanding, challenge stereotypes, and promote a culture of acceptance and respect. Join the new Pride Student Association Discord server! You do not need to be a member to attend our general body meetings. If you have any questions, feel free to reach out to us via e-mail.

organizations.name: Qualitative Research Club
organizations.description: The Qualitative Research Club is a community for graduate students, faculty, and staff with a vested interest in qualitative inquiry to connect, collaborate, learn, and create partnerships around new and ongoing research projects.

organizations.name: The Improv Academy
organizations.description: *If you are interested in joining The Improv Academy, please follow our Instagram for updates (@ucfimprov) or send us an email (ucftheimprovacademy@gmail.com)! The Improv Academy (TIA) teaches and performs long-form improvised comedy at the University of Central Florida. Our community is proudly to forges new friendships, fosters creativity, and shares a lot of laughs. The program is designed to support all levels of experience.   The Improv Academy functions foremost as an educational organization. Our program is divided into four levels and can be completed in two years. Each level takes a semester to complete. After finishing the program, players join our Grad Room.

organizations.name: Table Tennis Club @ UCF
organizations.description: Please follow the Instagram: instagram.com/tabletennis.ucf Current Practice Schedule (Starting 9/2): Tuesday 8:00-11:30pm at RWC Court 4 Wednesday 8:45-11:30pm at RWC Group Exercise 2 Sunday 12:00-3:00pm at RWC Court 4. All levels welcome!

organizations.name: American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics
organizations.description: Bridging the gap between students and the aerospace industry through projects, tours, workshops, events, and more! Join our Discord for updates and connect with members! https://discord.gg/phUHGKvG   We are the UCF student-chapter of the world's foremost technical society dedicated to the aerospace profession, AIAA .   Our student section is one of the largest registered student organizations (RSOs) on campus and the largest chapter of AIAA in the nation. We are primarily comprised of students majoring in Aerospace, Mechanical, and Electrical Engineering alongside Computer Science, but we welcome any interested students at UCF.   AIAA UCF's main activities include general body meetings, hands-on projects, social activities, community STEM outreach, tours, workshops, and guest speaker events. While our projects each have their own timelines, AIAA UCF holds at least one general body meeting a month; to keep with tradition, usually on the first Thursday of the month.   In 2025-2026 we continue to showcase our repeating projects of Rocket Design, Quadcopters, Hovercrafts, Aviation Vehicle Design (AVD), and Design Build Fly (DBF), along with two new experimental projects: VTOL and our very own high-powered rocketry project (Project Horizon). These projects all begin after our first general body meeting the first Thursday of September so be sure to show up for project presentations and an introduction to the club with free pizza.   More information about AIAA UCF and paying yearly dues can be found on our website ! For current members and interested students, please join our Discord Server for all updates!

organizations.name: Biology Graduate Student Association
organizations.description: The Biology Graduate Student Association (BGSA) provides UCF biology graduate students extracurricular activities including regular seminars, journal discussions, and social events. BGSA is also a service organization participating in outreach events and environmental cleanup activities.

organizations.name: Students for Training, Research, and Education in Energy and Turbines
organizations.description: STREET(Students for Training, Research, and Education in Energy and Turbines) is a student club. The main objective of the STREET is to train, research, and educate students. Also, it is the largest group for energy and turbine at UCF! We work on several different projects including power generation, aviation, and propulsion. We travel to national and international conferences together to present our works. We do have several fun events !!

organizations.name: Scholastic Association of Graduates in Engineering
organizations.description: SAGE is a CECS student organization committed to serving the needs of graduate students and BS-to-MS students in engineering and computer science. Our mission is to provide the resources to help students succeed personally, professionally, and academically. To that end, we try to present interesting speakers and useful information at all of our meetings, to provide insights or education in topics ranging from career development and job-seeking, to research skills and technical writing, to work-life balance and mental health. We also host social events to give students a chance to take a break from classwork and research and to meet fellow students outside of their individual labs and departments. Additionally, our organization serves as an advocate, not only listening to the needs of our members and representing their interests with the CECS and UCF administration, but also representing the CECS graduate program as a whole in recruiting new graduate students and providing guidance and support to undergraduates considering applying to graduate school. Most importantly, we want to help build a community that unites graduate students across CECS, regardless of where they come from, what they're studying, or where they are in their career. In a world where STEM research and industry are increasingly collaborative, interdisciplinary, and interdependent, it's more important than ever to have a diverse network of peers to rely on for information, mentorship, and support.

organizations.name: Future Theme Park Leaders Association
organizations.description: The Future Theme Park Leaders Association (FTPLA) is a professional student-run organization at the University of Central Florida's Rosen College of Hospitality Management. We strive to support the next and upcoming leaders in the theme park and attraction industry, worldwide. We do this by empowering our members to participate in numerous career building opportunities through networking with guest speakers in the industry, to visiting theme parks locally, nationally, and internationally. FTPLA witnesses incredible growth from its members through these career advancement opportunities. This has led to many members receiving internships and various, unique positions within our vast theme park industry by using skills garnered from FTPLA experiences.     FTPLA is the Rosen College's largest and longest running Registered Student Organization, and for more than 20 years, and many more to come, we plan to create waves and send ripples of leadership throughout the theme park industry.     FTPLA welcomes any and all students of the University of Central Florida- it's never too late to join the organization "for the thrill of it"

organizations.name: Audio Engineering Society
organizations.description: To provide a community for individuals interested in sound, music, engineering etc. regardless of their major or interest. For more information about meeting times and club activities, join our Discord. https://discord.gg/Dwe4dDnBnf

organizations.name: National Marrow Donor Program at UCF
organizations.description: NMDP at UCF is a student-led organization focused on education, recruitment, and fundraising to support patients in need of marrow and stem cell transplants. Our mission is to raise awareness about blood cancers, disorders, and the importance of donor registration. Education efforts include workshops, campus events, and drives that aim to dispel myths and provide accurate information about the donation process. By fostering informed conversations, we help students understand how they can make a life-saving impact. Fundraising supports both patient-centered initiatives and our on-campus activities. Funds raised go toward outreach, research support, and hosting events that strengthen our community's ability to contribute meaningfully. Recruitment involves engaging students and the campus community through events designed to connect potential donors to opportunities for joining the donor registry. We guide individuals through the process and help them take the first step toward becoming a match. Text "UCF" to 61474 to learn more or start your journey today.

organizations.name: Forensic Science Association
organizations.description: Interested in Forensic Science? Join the Forensic Science Association! Members will have the chance to tour local law enforcement agencies, attend lectures and workshops with forensic professionals, learn about new forensic techniques, conduct interative experiments demonstrating forensic topics, and attend the American Academy of Forensic Science conference! Email us to be added to our list for more information about meetings, events, and more!

organizations.name: Her Campus UCF
organizations.description: Her Campus UCF is a national online magazine for college women and professional development. We publish editorial and social media content on a weekly basis and hold campus wide events. At UCF, we have an editorial team, marketing team, social media team, and event planning team. Her Campus focuses on empowering college students, especially women, to feel confident about their academic career by creating a community on campus that helps develop social and professional skills needed to help you feel ready and confident in taking that next step toward your career. At Her Campus UCF, you learn valuable skills, build your portfolio and resume, network with your peers and industry professionals and have the support of a national organization. At the same time you also become part of a close knit group of women right here at UCF. Beyond your individual team responsibilities, you will have the opportunity to participate in team bonding events as well as our on and off campus events. Follow us on Instagram (@hercampusucf) for application info, event updates, and more!

organizations.name: Student Professionals for Industrial Organizational Psychology
organizations.description: SPIOP's mission is to promote graduate and undergraduate student understanding and involvement within the field of Industrial/Organizational Psychology, and to bridge the opportunities and resources that are available to us in the Business School, Psychology Department, and across the university. Subscribe to our email list to stay informed of upcoming SPIOP meetings and events. Learn more about SPIOP on our  website.

organizations.name: OSI Volunteerism and Community Engagement
organizations.description: The Volunteerism and Community Engagement Center (VCE) is a part of the Office of Student Involvement (OSI), located in suite 154 of the Student Union. We focus on volunteerism and community engagement within our UCF community and in the Greater Orlando community. VCE now houses the Alternative Break program, Volunteer UCF, AmeriCorps, Community Connectors, as well as other programs, organizations, and initiatives connected to volunteerism.

organizations.name: Knights Emergency Medical Response Unit
organizations.description: The mission of Knights Emergency Medical Responders is to support the health, safety, and wellness of our community by connecting campus first responders, and raising awareness of life-saving care. Members will gain medical knowledge, clinical experience, learn emergency skills, explore EMS career options, and create fun memories!   To be a part of club meetings, skills workshops, and other fun events join us on KnightConnect and follow us on Instagram @ucfkemru ! If you are a certified EMS professional and would like to join our Response Unit that will gain hands on clinical experience, apply now with this form !   Co-Presidents and Founders: Rylie Manning and Sarah Quinones

organizations.name: Student Government Election Commission
organizations.description: The Election Commission  serves to promote and facilitate Student Government elections. The Election Commission is comprised of the Supervisor of Elections, the Assistant Supervisor of Elections, and 12 other Election Commissioners. Together, they successfully market, facilitate, and execute the Elections! They also ensure that all candidates and campaigners abide by the Election Statutes and enjoy a fair and transparent election experience.     Potential candidates can find the Candidate Application Packets in the "Forms" section of the Election Commission Knight Connect page. Presidential petition sheets can be found in the "Documents" section of the Election Commission Knight Connect page. Please convert the Petition sheets to a .csv file upon submission.    2025 Fall Events: Prospective Presidential and Senate Candidates Q&A Date and Time: Wednesday, November 12th, 5:00 PM - 7:00 PM Location: Live Oak Event Center ‚Äì Magnolia Room   2026 Election Period Timeline:   2026 Info Sessions! Time: 10:15 AM - 11:00 AM Location: Sand Key, SU Room 220   Dates: January 27th,  January 29th, February 3rd, February 5th, February 6th, February 9th, February 10th, and February 11th   Virtual (Zoom) Dates: February 13th (12:00 PM - 12:45 PM) and February 17th (9:00 AM - 9:45 AM)   Important Dates: Election Period Begins & Presidential Petition Forms Open: Monday, January 12th, 9:00 AM   Declaration of Candidacy Period: Monday-Friday, February 9th-13th, 9:00 AM - 5:00 PM   Active Campaigning Allowed Beginning: Monday, February 9th, 9:00 AM -  Candidates may campaign only after receiving verification from the Election Commission.
