organizations.name: Phi Alpha Delta Pre-Law Fraternity
organizations.description: https://www.pad.org/page/JoinPAD Connect with us on Instagram   Phi Alpha Delta Law Fraternity, International is a professional law fraternity advancing integrity, compassion and courage through service to the student, the school, the profession and the community. We are the preeminent law fraternity promoting the bonds of fraternalism and we are the leader in the development and advancement of professional ideals. The purpose of this Fraternity shall be to form a strong bond uniting students and teachers of the law with members of the Bench and Bar in a fraternal fellowship designed to advance the ideals of liberty and equal justice under law; to stimulate excellence in scholarship; to inspire the virtues of compassion and courage; to foster integrity and professional competence; to promote the welfare of its members; and to encourage their moral, intellectual, and cultural advancement; so that each member may enjoy a lifetime of honorable professional and public service.

organizations.name: Art Club
organizations.description: This organization's goal is to provide an outlet for creative expression, establish an artistic community, and further development of our members abilities toward expressing themselves through visual imagery. We hope to bring many artists and admirers together for a common interest of the love for art in which they can  learn new skills, share their work, develop connections, improve their creative abilities and have a great time in our open and supportive community. Announcements for our events are listed on our Discord below: Art Club Server Art Club Carrd

organizations.name: Youth Evangelical Fellowship at University of Central Florida
organizations.description: The Mission of Youth Evangelical Fellowship at University of Central Florida" is to offer deep studies that would provide spiritual guidance for universities at different levels of their faith. All fellowship, prayer, and bible reading will give students a deeper understanding of the Word of God and their desire to live a life that truly honors the Lord. We want to give students the opportunity to also evangelize on campus throughout the week, become campus leaders in teaching the word, and contribute to the betterment of the UCF/Orlando area through community service events, hosting local retreats, and deep Bible Studies offered throughout the week during every semester.

organizations.name: Future Technical Communicators
organizations.description: Looking for a job after graduation?  FTC can help! The Future Technical Communicators (FTC) student organization here at UCF is dedicated to helping students pursue careers in technical communication. What exactly does that mean? We work together to master the skills we will need once we graduate to create any kind of documentation for technical processes. That can mean everything from writing instructions to designing user-friendly websites. This organization is primarily intended for students who are interested in pursuing careers in the technical communication field, although membership is open to students from all majors.    Even if you are not familiar with the profession, technical communication might be the field for you! Do you have skills in any of these areas? * Core skills in writing and editing * Creative page design * Photography and videography * Technical illustration * International communication * Training and education * Web and IT skills   Technical communicators serve as the bridge between technology and the outside world. We take complex information and make accessible and exciting! Technical communication spans many disciplines and the job market is huge. Unless technology stands still, it will always be a growth market. Since companies are beginning to realize that poor writing and poor communication hurt their bottom line, solving that problem taps into your core skills. There are over 45,000 technical writers in the U.S. alone!   FTC can also help you gain experience by obtaining an internship and part-time opportunities. Some of the companies include Lockheed Martin, Orlando Utilities Commision, Citrix, and many more. For additional employment opportunities please contact ucf.ftc@gmail.com or message us on one of our platforms .    We are eager to see you at our next event! Make sure to connect with us on Discord , LinkedIn, and social media for more information.

As part of UCF's Panhellenic Council, Kappa Delta actively participates in various campus activities, including philanthropic events, community service, and leadership development programs. organizations.name: YEHUDI
organizations.description: By offering dynamic programming, thrilling social events, beautiful venues, international trips, and stimulating growth opportunities, YEHUDI forges eternal bonds and sparks the YEHUDI in you. organizations.name: The Balkan Student Association

organizations.description: The purpose of this chapter shall be to bring about a union of Omega men on the local, state, district and national levels who manifest high ideals of manhood, scholarship, perseverance, and uplift in order to: a)    Stimulate the attainment of high ideals; b)    Disseminate and inculcate these ideals among those with whom it comes in contact; c)    Occupy a progressive and constructive place in the civic life of the community, state and nation; d)    Keep Omega forever burning in the hearts of her gallant sons; and e)    Remind the brothers of their responsibility to keep Omega forever progressive and strong.

organizations.name: Chi Alpha Christian Fellowship

organizations.name: Pegasus Pilots

organizations.name: LGBTQ+ Services
organizations.description: The UCF Student Government established the Lesbian Gay Bisexual Transgender Questioning/Queer (LGBTQ+) Student Support Services to connect our diverse student population to opportunities, resources, and each other. Funded by the Activity and Service Fee, its mission is to achieve the vision of a stronger, healthier, and more equitable world for all individuals including LGBTQ+ people and their allies. Student Government continues to support this area, ensuring it remains a welcoming space for all students. LGBTQ+ strives to support the community by: Fostering greater opportunities for students to succeed at UCF. Helping organize programs and experiences geared toward educating the UCF community about issues surrounding the LGBTQ+ community. Creating a forum where LGBTQ+ history and culture is acknowledged, discussed, and celebrated. Creating a space where resources can be created and explored in the future. LGBTQ+ Student Support Services is a resource office open to all students, including LGBTQ+ students and allies. We are an entry point for anyone looking for resources relating to sexual orientation or gender identity. LGBTQ+ Services' grand opening was celebrated on October 11, 2011 which was also National Coming Out Day. Lavender Council A student advisory board that serves as a liaison between students, faculty, and staff and LGBTQ+ Student Support Services. They work to make UCF a more accepting and welcoming campus by developing and advising on student-centered programs. They strive to make UCF a more equitable campus through programming and events to educate the UCF community about issues regarding the LGBTQ+ community. Pride Commons Located in Ferrell Commons across from 63 South, Pride Commons is a place for UCF students looking for resources, a community, a place to hang out, or a quiet place to study. It is open to all students of all genders and sexual orientations. The Pride Commons is staffed by Civil Discourse & Engagement Staff members, the Multicultural Student Center Executive Board, and student assistants.

organizations.name: Register Student Organization (RSO) Resources
organizations.description: Welcome to the RSO Resources Hub!  This page serves as your one-stop resource to assist you with the registration/re-registration process and answer any questions about your Registered Student Organization (RSO). We're here to make your experience seamless and successful!     New Organization Registration: New Organization Registration is now open! Please scroll down and find the form. The form will close November 10th.   Looking to Reactivate your RSO? Please schedule an appointment with one of our Graduate Assistants. Ellie: https://calendly.com/el910486-ucf/30min Jake:  https://calendly.com/ja923053-ucf/30min   ASO/DSSO Organizations: If your organization believes it qualifies as an ASO or DSSO, you must email your completed Sponsorship Form and Advisor Agreement form to RSO@ucf.edu and Angely.Tolani@ucf.edu. Please note that there are specific forms for ASO and specific forms for DSSOs, make sure you are submitting the correct set for your classification. OSI will review your submission, and once approved, we will notify you of your official ASO or DSSO classification. Only organizations with official OSI approval will be classified as ASO or DSSO.    What's New?   We've introduced new RSO Classifications to better support your organization's needs. Here's a quick breakdown:   - GSO (General Student Organization): Independent student-led groups focused on a shared interest or mission.   - DSSO (Departmental Supported Student Organization): Directly supported by a university department, with resources and advising provided.   **College/Department/Unit approval required** - ASO (Associated Student Organization): Affiliated with campus-wide initiatives or umbrella organizations. **College/Department/Unit approval required**    This change ensures clearer support structures and helps streamline processes for all RSOs.     Required Materials: In order to create a new student organization, you must follow the steps and collect all the information to complete the application: New Organization Consultation  A constitution (scroll down to the "Files" section of this page for a helpful template). At least 10 UCF student members with NID emails Organization President and at least 1 other officer UCF Staff Advisor (NOT REQUIRED, but HIGHLY ENCOURAGED) Mission that is unique, and not a duplicate of an existing RSO External Affiliation documents (if applicable) -If they are a branch from an existing organization An organization name that does NOT include the University of Central Florida/UCF preceding the name of their RSO (ex. UCF Hiking Knights is not a valid name)   To schedule a new organization consultation, visit: https://calendly.com/kortoutreach     Need a Banking Letter?   Submit a Banking Letter form found under Knight of the Roundtable's KnightConnect Page. Click here to access the form. Available Forms   You'll find the following forms on this site:   - New Organization Registration (available until November 10th) - Constitution Revision Request   - Student Leader Eligibility Appeals    Additional Resources A constitution template is available in the Documents section of this webpage.   Questions?  Please take a look to familiarize yourself with our RSO Manual . It is a great resource for all student organizations. You can access it here: RSO Manual       - RSO Coordinator, Angely Tolani: angely.tolani@ucf.edu  - RSO Graduate Assistants: rso@ucf.edu     Office Information   Location: Office of Student Involvement, Student Union 208   Email: osi@ucf.edu   Phone: (407) 823-6471

organizations.name: Knight PALS for Autism
organizations.description: Knight PALS is a student organization at the University of Central Florida. Our goals are to provide support for neurodivergent individuals on campus and promote autism acceptance within the Central Florida community through self-determination enhancement programs, including workshops, social events, and trainings.

organizations.name: Psychedelic Science Club
organizations.description: Psychedelic Science Club at UCF is a student-led organization dedicated to exploring the scientific, medical, and interdisciplinary study of psychedelics. Our mission is to create a welcoming space for students to learn, discuss, and engage with this rapidly growing field through an academic lens. We focus on: Education : Hosting speaker events, workshops, and reading groups to share knowledge on psychedelic research, history, and policy. Research Opportunities : Connecting students to labs, conferences, and faculty doing work related to neuroscience, psychology, pharmacology, and anthropology. Harm Reduction & Wellness : Promoting evidence-based harm reduction practices and fostering honest, stigma-free conversations about mental health. Community & Collaboration : Building an inclusive, interdisciplinary community of curious students and collaborating with other campus organizations for events, service, and outreach. Whether you're passionate about neuroscience, psychology, pharmacology, public health, philosophy, anthropology, or simply curious about the future of psychedelic science, you'll find a place here to learn, connect, and contribute.

organizations.name: Japanese Language Club
organizations.description: About the Japanese Language Club - Êó•Êú¨Ë™ûÈÉ®Ê¥ª„Å´„Å§„ÅÑ„Å¶ Japanese Language Club (JLC) is a UCF student club for learners of the Japanese Language. With a large emphasis on real practice and community building, JLC stands as a place for all levels of Japanese learners to get together and encourage each other to reach fluency! Real Practice With weekly General Body Meetings as well as Kaiwa Table (Japanese Conversation Table), we hold frequent events in which Japanese learners can practice reading real native content and communicating through real-world scenarios. On top of this, several "special" GBMs are held in which learners can test their skills while participating in a fun activity! organizations.name: Alpha Delta Pi Sorority
organizations.description: Originally called the Adelphean Society, Alpha Delta Pi is the  first  secret society for women in the world and forged the way for women in the fraternity system. We were founded on May 15, 1851 at Wesleyan Female College ‚Äì the  first  college in the world chartered to grant degrees to women. Founder Eugenia Tucker Fitzgerald was just sixteen years old when she left her family to attend Wesleyan College. At such a young age and during a time when it was rare for women to go to college, she recognized the importance of women coming together for personal development and improvement. She and her five closest friends founded the Adelphean Society. In 1909, she wrote a letter to our Alpha chapter in which she states, "Whatever I have done worth remembering, I know that the founding of our society is one of them." https://www.ucfadpi.com/

organizations.name: Gift of Life
organizations.description: Please don't be afraid to reach out to us if you have any questions or would like to volunteer! We are always looking for new members. Join our Groupchat: https://groupme.com/join_group/60506953/WAN8xMCb Gift of Life's mission is to cure blood cancer through cellular therapy. At Gift of Life we believe every person battling blood cancer deserves a second chance at life ‚Äî and we are determined to make it happen. We are singularly passionate about engaging the public to help us get everyone involved in curing blood cancer, whether as a donor, a volunteer or a financial supporter. It all begins with one remarkable person, one life-changing swab and one huge win ‚Äî finding a match and a cure. On campus, our volunteers hold drives where we recruit young healthy donors to our registry who might one day have the amazing opportunity to voluntarily donate stem cells or bone marrow to a patient in need. Our work at UCF and other campuses has saved dozens of lives, and we are always looking for new volunteers to help us on this mission.

organizations.name: Delta Epsilon Psi
organizations.description: Delta Epsilon Psi is a South Asian interest social and service fraternity established in 1998 at the University of Texas at Austin. Their mission is to foster brotherhood, nurture the development of leadership, and promote service to the community. The fraternity was founded on the principles of brotherhood, discipline, and commitment. Brotherhood is about creating strong bonds of friendship, discipline is about striving for excellence in all aspects of life, and commitment is about dedicating oneself to the fraternity and its principles for life. Delta Epsilon Psi is also dedicated to spreading South Asian culture, with many chapters hosting cultural events and participating in cultural activities on their campuses. The fraternity also encourages academic achievement, with many chapters offering scholarships for its members. In terms of community service, Delta Epsilon Psi is heavily involved in various philanthropic activities. The fraternity has a close relationship with Breakthrough T1D (formerly JDRF), working to raise funds and awareness for Type 1 diabetes research. Additionally, the fraternity works with Be the Match to support the cause for stem cell transplant and research. Members of the fraternity often participate in volunteer work, fundraising events, and awareness campaigns to help fight this disease. By 2025, Delta Epsilon Psi has grown significantly and now has many chapters across the United States. The fraternity's members are active on their campuses and in their communities, living out the organization's values of brotherhood, discipline, and commitment. Delta Epsilon Psi continues to promote the advancement of South Asian culture, awareness of important social issues, and the development of leadership skills among its members. They continue to strive to make a difference in their communities and uphold the ideals upon which the fraternity was founded.

organizations.name: The Adaptive Community
organizations.description: The Adaptive Community/Aphasia Family meets at 12:30-3:30 pm every Friday during the academic terms at UCF (spring, summer, fall).  - Meetings occur from 12:30-2:30 for Aphasia Family members,  - Volunteers collaborate on Aphasia Family projects from 2:30-3:30.    Contact: Interested in volunteering? Email us for access to our application! For general inquiries, contact aphasiafamily@ucf.edu.    Description of Aphasia Family:   Aphasia Family is a free community group that provides language-rich activities, socialization, and community outings for stroke survivors with aphasia and related communication disorders. Aphasia Family is offered as one of the UCF Aphasia House programs, and the group was founded by people with aphasia, for people with aphasia. The weekly Aphasia Family meetings, led by undergraduate and graduate students, foster intergenerational dialogue between members with communication disorders and UCF students.  . If you have questions regarding the Aphasia House that do not pertain to volunteering, please contact Aphasia House Interim Director, Dr. Lauren Bislick Wilson at lauren.bislick@ucf.edu.  . Remember to dress appropriately when volunteering with the Adaptive Community. At The Aphasia House, we are expected to come dressed professionally. No shorts, jeans, hats, T-shirts, tennis shoes, or conspicuous logos. Thank you!     Page updated: 08/21/2025

organizations.name: Global Medical Brigades
organizations.description: Global Brigades is the world's largest student-led global health and sustainable development organization. Since 2004, Global Brigades has mobilized tens of thousands of university students and professionals through skill-based programs that work in partnership with community members to improve quality of life in under resourced regions while respecting local culture.   The mission of our Medical Brigade here in UCF is to provide comprehensive health care in rural communities with limited access to healthcare by having volunteers work alongside local licensed medical professionals. Our current focus is in Ghana, Honduras, Guatemala, Belize, Greece and Panama. Medical Brigade volunteers have the opportunity to shadow licensed professionals in consultations and assist in filling necessary prescriptions under the direction of a licensed pharmacists. Each of our partner communities receives a brigade every 3 to 6 months where hundreds of patients are provided one on one consultations, public health workshops, and given the proper medication or referral. Electronic patient records are collected through Data Informatics to monitor overall community health trends. Between brigades our in-country team maintains relationships with the communities to provide follow-up care and education.    Volunteer brigade participation may vary based on the medical background and skill of the volunteer. Volunteers with little to no medical experience have the opportunity to assist during triage, shadow doctors during consultations, deliver educational workshops, and help pack medications under the supervision of a local pharmacist. All patient consultations as well as the prescribing of medications is done only by licensed doctors. Regardless of medical skill level, all volunteers contribute to the clinic. Furthermore, volunteers have the opportunity to learn about providing sustainable healthcare to rural communities who would otherwise have limited access.   To become a member fill out the following: https://form.jotform.com/251405495897066

As political, economic, and social forces continue to deprive women, transgender, and non-binary people of safety from viole nce, fair and equal treatment in the workplace, access to reproductive healthcare and comprehensive sex education, and much more both in this country and abroad ‚Äì it's crucial that young feminists take initiative to raise awareness about the persisting need for gender equality, as well as leading the way to take action. organizations.description: The African Students' Organization or ASO , is committed to promoting African culture to the UCF campus and surrounding community through dance, music, poetry and more. We also hold many spectacular events throughout the year that are meant to educate our community about the various wonders of Africa. Many times, we will partner with other UCF organizations to jointly show the uniqueness of our respective cultures while unifying with others. ASO always welcomes anyone who has an interest in learning more about Africa, and seeks to be an integral social, academic, and cultural part of the college experience of everyone at UCF. ASO Goals: (1) To unite African students studying at UCF  (2) Create a medium for African students to socialize and interact (3) To enrich the UCF and local communities through unique African events, programs, and other community-based activities. (4) To provide networking opportunities for and with African students inside and outside the African community. (5) To correctly inform UCF and the rest of the world about issues affecting Africa and combat any misinformation about African peoples and countries. (6) To provide a forum for the discussion and debate of matters of special interest to African liberation development.

organizations.name: Fraternity and Sorority Life
organizations.description: At UCF we recognize 45 Greek organizations with a population over 3,000 undergraduate students.  Each organization offers something unique as they all share common values which lead to life-long bonds of friendship.  Greek organizations play a vital role in helping provide students with a wealth of experiences which complement the educational mission of the University. How to Join Must be a registered UCF student Must have a minimum cumulative 2.5 high school or college GPA Must be mutual selected by an organization through the recruitment process, for more information about how to join visit https://fsl.sswb.ucf.edu/how-to-join/   Councils Greek Council Serves as the unifying link between all chapters and councils and is responsible for annual Fraternity and Sorority Life events such as Greek Week, Greek Leadership Challenge, and Trick or Treat on Greek Street. Diversified Greek Council (DGC)  https://fsl.sswb.ucf.edu/diversified-greek/  DGC is comprised of 12 fraternities and sororities from a variety of cultural backgrounds and caters to those who want to get involved with others who share culture, beliefs, and interests.  National Pan-Hellenic Council (NPHC) https://fsl.sswb.ucf.edu/national-pan-hellenic/ NPHC is home to 9 historically African-American fraternities and sororities that foster brotherhood and sisterhood within the African-American community on campus. Interfraternity Council (IFC) https://fsl.sswb.ucf.edu/interfraternity/ IFC consists of 13 organizations committed to enriching the collegiate and fraternity experience for over 1000 fraternity men on our campus. Panhellenic Council (PAN) https://fsl.sswb.ucf.edu/panhellenic/ The Panhellenic Council consists of 12 women's organizations who strive for excellence in every aspect to form an amazing community and enrich the lives of collegiate women. Greek Park Greek Park currently has 13 Greek facilities, with 3 houses being occupied by fraternities and 10 by sororities. Greek Park is a natural gathering spot for Greek students. A recent addition to Greek Park is the Office of Fraternity and Sorority Life Building. Why Go Greek? Academics:   All-Greek GPA averages are consistently/generally higher than the All-UCF GPA average Leadership Opportunities: Members of the UCF Greek community are active in Student Government, President's Leadership Council, Order of Pegasus, LEAD Scholars, Orientation Team, and Academic Honor Societies etc.         Service and Philanthropy: Each year UCF Greeks log over approximately 80,000 hours of community service and collect over $645,000 for various local and national philanthropic organizations, and donate over 50,000 lbs. of food to local shelters Social Life: Athletics and intramurals teams, sisterhood and brotherhood mixers and themed socials, formals and date functions.

organizations.name: UCF Student Health Services
organizations.description: UCF Student Health Services provides high-quality healthcare that delivers value, promotes lifelong well-being, and supports academic success within the UCF community. We aspire to be the model college health program of the future that will transform the health and well-being of the community we serve. Since its establishment in 1968, UCF Student Health Services has grown tremendously and today averages 6,000 patient visits per month. We provide low-cost health services to the UCF community and are funded, in part, by the student Health Fee, which is included in students' tuition. We are committed to providing the UCF community with quality healthcare, and as such maintain accreditation by the Accreditation Association for Ambulatory Health Care (AAAHC). In addition to providing primary and specialty healthcare services to our Knights, UCF SHS is one of several departments that comprise UCF Well-Being, a partnership that focuses on health and wellness-oriented programming. Both together and individually, we plan, coordinate, and host well-being events designed to educate our Knights on important health topics within a fun, supportive environment. https://linktr.ee/ucf.shs

organizations.name: Counselor Education Doctoral Students Organization
organizations.description: The Counselor Education Doctoral Student Organization (CEDSO) is the student association specifically for doctoral students in counselor education at UCF. Formed in 2008, the mission of the CEDSO is to promote the development of counselor education doctoral students in the areas of scholarship, teaching, and service through mentoring and collaboration opportunities.  The mentoring initiative began in 2011, with second and third year students volunteering as mentors for incoming first years.  CEDSO also applies to the SGA for funding to assist members in attending the ACES or SACES conference every fall.  Member collaboration is facilitated through semester meetings and social functions.  Additionally, CEDSO has recently launched a new Facebook page that can assist in answering questions for new and current students, including conference deadlines and member contact information.

organizations.name: Transfer Knights
organizations.description: Welcome to Transfer Knights! Transfer Knights is the one-stop shop for integrating into campus either as a first-time transfer student or any semester afterward. We host general body meetings that consist of fun activities that allow you to get to know other students on campus in addition to providing workshops and resources that are provided both on and off campus.  Aside from academic events, we also host socials and ways to get to know people through meetups, tailgating during football games, spirit splash, and so much more. Transfer students make up a majority of the population of our UCF community and we want you to have fun and get involved! We encourage you attend as many events as possible and give out prizes such as Member of the Month and a monetary scholarship based on attendance.  If you have questions or just want to chat, message one of our executive board leaders.   Our Social Media & More: LinkTree: https://linktr.ee/transferknights Instagram: @ transferknights Discord :  https://discord.gg/2P3wcdDY3Y Website :  https://transferknights.weebly.com/   Our Spring 2025 Executive Board: President - Reya Colón Vice President - Ivan Iliev Recruitment Director - Javier Narvaez-Martinez Events Coordinator - Jazmin Wiggins   Graduate Student Advisor - Nishit Tailor

organizations.name: University Kinesiology Club
organizations.description: The University Kinesiology Club (UKC), cooperating with professional organizations, related fields, and our community, strives to be recognized as a national presence advancing the Sport and Exercise Science field, and the well being of all people through participation, leadership, advocacy, and professional conduct in our professions. UKC brings together students interested in personal training, athletic training, physical therapy, occupational therapy, sports medicine, chiropractic and more! -- To become a member, you must pay your club dues (cash or our Venmo link, which we can provide upon request), of either $20 for the semester or $35 for the year. After which you will be approved to join the official roster here on Knight Connect. Members will receive a club t-shirt, access to member only events and volunteer opportunities, and more! If you have any questions, our contact information can be found below. Please click on the website button to visit our Linktree  and Instagram !

organizations.name: Women's Law Student Association
organizations.description: Our club strives to empower women in the law field that is typically run by men. Our members will focus on study groups for the LSAT and networking for internships to be successful. We want everyone to succeed and work together to achieve the goal of getting into law school. Applications, studying for the LSAT, and finding internships is all very stressful along with school work that we already have, and that is what we are here for.

organizations.name: Campus Activities Board
organizations.description: Our goal is to push the boundaries of campus events by providing diverse and unique entertainment for the UCF student body and the Orlando community. We are funded through the Activity and Service Fee, allocated to the Campus Activities Board through Student Government. Each of our eight (8) committee directors are responsible for the execution of a specific types of events relating to the respective committee. The overall function and direction of the organization are managed by the Executive and Associate Directors of the Campus Activities Board.   How to Get Involved If you are interested in getting involved with the Campus Activities Board, email our CAB Associate Director, Lauren Walker, at cabassociate@ucf.edu for more information.    Mission Our mission at UCF's Campus Activities Board (CAB) is to foster a sense of community on campus by hosting unique events that effectively cater to our diverse student body and the Orlando community.    Contact Us   Natalie Mendez Executive Director   cab@ucf.edu She/Her/Hers   Lauren Walker Associate Director   cabassociate@ucf.edu She/Her/Hers   Mary-Kate Starr Cinema Director   cabcinema@ucf.edu She/Her/Hers   Antonio Mitchell Comedy Director   cabcomedy@ucf.edu He/Him/His   Aubrey Hunter Concerts Director   cabconcerts@ucf.edu She/Her/Hers   Nyla Julmisse Fine Arts Director   cabarts@ucf.edu She/Her/Hers   Alexis Butler Impact Director   cabimpact@ucf.edu She/Her/Hers   Marley Vose Promotions Director   cabpromotions@ucf.edu She/Her/Hers   Lance Lozano Digital Media Director   cabmarketing@ucf.edu He/Him/His   Sara Benyamine Special Events Director   cabevent@ucf.edu She/Her/Hers

organizations.name: Financial Forecasting Club
organizations.description: Our goal is to create a group of individuals passionate about financial markets and investing who can come together and collaborate on creating financial models and forecasts to expand their knowledge on financial forecasting and investing while helping others learn as well. We are currently trying to build a good group of members and will start having meetings and events in the fall semester.

organizations.name: Nursing Unidos - Hispanic Nursing Student Association
PERIOD @ UCF
organizations.description: PERIOD@UCF aims to educate on and advocate for menstrual equity and is dedicated to philanthropic and charitable services to the student, local, national, and global communities. We strive to do so by donating PERIOD packs, partnering with local organizations, educating the community, pushing for period policy changes, and fostering productive conversation about the stigma and topic in general.   2025 - 2026 Executive Board: Co-presidents: Meera Lakshmanan & Ritisha Suresh Vice President: Shreyaashri Selvakumar Treasurer: Madison Diaz Secretary: Spurthi Nrusimhadevara Media Relations: Mia Ladores

organizations.name: Ratio Christi @ UCF
organizations.description: Ratio Christi @ UCF aims to equip university students to give historical, philosophical, and scientific reasons for Christianity. We bring together faith and reason to establish the intellectual voice of Christ in the University. Students, engaged in the battle for the mind, learn to defend God's existence, the reliability of the Bible, and the reality of Christ's resurrection. Ratio Christi is a safe place to bring doubts, questions, and challenges to Christianity. Our goal is to ask the hard questions and come to reasonable conclusions.

organizations.name: Unmanned Spacecraft Engineering and Research Club
organizations.description: Mission The mission of Unmanned Spacecraft Engineering and Research Club is to Promote research and development in the are of unmanned spacecraft, as well as increase students exposure and knowledge of space systems. Goals The aim of our organization is education about small satellites through discussion, research, and hands on experience. We provide a way to get first hand experience with building satellites and exploring space.

organizations.name: Peruvian Student Association
organizations.description: Mission The mission of the Peruvian Student Association (PeruSA) is to socially, academically, and professionally unite all students, alumni, and faculty, by fostering and promoting the Peruvian culture at both the University of Central Florida and the overall Orlando community. Goals The goal of Peruvian Student Association (PeruSA) is to serve as a nucleus for networking with Peruvian students, alumni, faculty, and other regional or local organizations. It shall be open and accessible to everyone thus providing a cultural liaison between the Peruvian community and UCF at large. PeruSA will strive to raise awareness of Peruvian culture for the students at UCF and the community.

organizations.name: National Association of Health Services Executives at UCF
organizations.description: The mission of the National Association of Health Service Executives (NAHSE) at UCF is to promote the advancement and development of black healthcare leaders and elevate the quality of healthcare services rendered to minorities and underserved communities. NAHSE participates in local and national programs and projects designed to improve the quality, access, and availability of health services and to expand educational opportunities in the field of health services administration. Serves as the official liaison between national NAHSE and UCF.

organizations.name: Organization Test
organizations.description: Testing

organizations.name: Students for Education in Prison
organizations.description: We are a student-led club organized to support UCF faculty and students in prison education and related areas of civic engagement. Our goals include collaborating with other organizations to raise awareness of mass incarceration, discussing the impacts of education in prison, and hosting drives and events. SFEP is for everyone, regardless of their level of knowledge on issues of mass incarceration, and we aim to be a welcoming and supportive space for formerly incarcerated students.  Join us at an upcoming meeting! Come open to meeting people and learning new things!

organizations.name: Honors Congress
organizations.description: The Honors Congress exists to strengthen the Honors community by providing academic, volunteer and social outlets for Honors students. True excellence arises not from mere academics, but from a rounded character demonstrating a commitment to community involvement and integrity in all endeavors. With this in mind, the Honors Congress is committed to developing a diversified student body. The Honors Congress fosters a spirit of unity through the facilitation of social, academic and volunteer activities and cultivates a sense of community within The Burnett Honors College.

organizations.name: Central Florida Hillel
organizations.description: Hillel at UCF Engages Students with Israel :  Hillel at UCF views Israel as a core element of Jewish life and a gateway to Jewish identification for students. We provide every Jewish student with the opportunity to explore and build an enduring relationship with Israel through our Israel Fellowship, support of pro-Israel student groups, and Taglit-Birthright Israel.   Hillel at UCF Engages Students at a Critical Time in Their Lives : Hillel at UCF strives to engage and support all Jewish students who are away from home for the first time in their lives. Knowing that more than one of two students comes from an interfaith household, we also support the many unaffiliated students along their Jewish journeys through an exploration of their passions and interests as Jews and as young adults. Through an intensive effort to get to know the broader Jewish student body, we are better able to foster the meaningful Jewish experiences of our students.   Hillel at UCF Supports a Life of Jewish Meaning : Hillel at UCF creates a safe space for students to explore their Jewish identities, embark in Jewish learning experiences, and celebrate our Jewish heritage.    Hillel at UCF Builds the Leaders of Tomorrow : Hillel at UCF fosters the next generation of Jewish leaders by providing our Knights with leadership training, faculty mentoring, and by connecting students to each other and to the broader UCF alumni network. Hillel at UCF Repairs The World : Hillel at UCFinspires and provides students with opportunities to demonstrate a commitment to social justice, volunteerism, and community service through ongoing and special events that serve our local community, Florida and the entire world.

organizations.name: Panhellenic Council
organizations.description: The UCF Panhellenic Council is the governing body over the twelve National Panhellenic Conference (NPC) sororities located on our campus. The Council is comprised of ten executive officers, chapter presidents, twelve chapter delegates, and junior delegates. It is the responsibility of the Council to unite all chapters in the spirit of Greek unity, to enforce the NPC guidelines, and to oversee and regulate the recruitment process. The Council works year round to promote positive ideals of sorority life at UCF, and contribute to the UCF community through involvement, leadership, academic, philanthropy, school spirit, and overall support.

organizations.name: Theta Tau Professional Engineering Fraternity
organizations.description: Are you a student in the college of engineering and computer science looking to make friends with other students who share similar interests? Do you want more of the college experience, while at the same time preparing yourself for the career of your dreams? Since 1904, Theta Tau has been providing a brotherhood for engineers. Theta Tau is the nation's oldest and foremost fraternity for engineers. The purpose of Theta Tau is to develop and maintain a high standard of professional interest among its members, and to unite them in a strong bond of fraternal fellowship. If you're looking to get more out of your education while having fun at the same time, then Theta Tau may be the fraternity for you. Come out to our Fall or Spring semester Rush events to hang out and get to know the brothers of Theta Tau Rho Gamma Chapter.

organizations.name: Phi Delta Theta International Fraternity
organizations.description: Being part of a fraternity would also involve upholding certain traditions, rituals, and values that are important to the organization. These could include community service, philanthropy, leadership, and academic excellence. As a member, I would be expected to embody these values and to contribute to the overall mission of the fraternity.

organizations.name: Kappa Alpha Psi Fraternity Inc.
organizations.description: To unite college men of culture, patriotism, and honor in a bond of Fraternity; To encourage honorable achievement in every field of human endeavor; To promote the spiritual, social, intellectual, and moral welfare of members; To assist the aims and purposes of Colleges and Universities; To inspire service in the public interest.

organizations.name: Puerto Rican Student Association- Central Florida
organizations.description: The Puerto Rican Student Association-Central Florida serves as a liaison between the UCF and the Puerto Rican community to support and unite Puerto Rican students at UCF. PRSA-CF is committed to providing social, cultural, and educational awareness among the UCF community about the Puerto Rican people. We want to create a safe space where Puerto Rican can embrace their culture and feel close to home.  The goal of PRSA-CF is to unite the Puerto Rican students at UCF to help and support each other throughout their educational journey at UCF. Also, PRSA-CF, like UCF, stands for opportunity. This organization will make sure that its members excel at UCF by providing them with proper leadership and personal growth experiences. PRSA-CF will offer a safe, comfortable, and judging-free environment for Puerto Rican students to come together and smoothly adjust to campus life. Discussions about personal experiences and cultural diversity will serve as the primary source for developing harmony and friendship among all of its members and the rest of the UCF student body. PRSA-CF, as the acting Puerto Rican institution at UCF, will look after the educational and social development and progress of the Puerto Rican community in Orlando and Central Florida.

organizations.name: Global Knights Society
organizations.description: The Global Knights Society is a club dedicated to easing the transition of life abroad for international students staying at UCF each semester. GKS is dedicated to ensuring every member feels welcome and connected within our organization. We host multiple events each semester that allow for members, our ambassadors, to bond with the exchange and learn about other cultures and norms. These events provide an opportunity to make life long, meaningful connections with people all across the world.

organizations.name: Alpha Epsilon Phi Sorority
organizations.description: Alpha Epsilon Phi is a national sorority dedicated to helping women become the best they can be. We promote individuality; encouraging each member to discover and develop the talents and abilities that make her unique.

organizations.name: Chilean Student Association
organizations.description: The Chilean Student Association (CHISA) is a safe space for Chileans and anyone interested in our culture to come together as one to celebrate and learn about it. Join us!
